  "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/11377944/parsing-a-hexadecimal-string-to-an-integer-throws-a-numberformatexception",
  "title" : "Parsing a Hexadecimal String to an Integer throws a NumberFormatException?",
  "body" : "<p>So, In Java, you know how you can declare integers like this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>int hex = 0x00ff00;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>I thought that you should be able to reverse that process. I have this code:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Integer.valueOf(primary.getFullHex());\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>where primary is an object of a custom Color class. It's constructor takes an Integer for opacity (0-99) and a hex String (e.g. <code>00ff00</code>).</p>\n\n<p>This is the <code>getFullHex</code> method:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public String getFullHex() {\n    return (\"0x\" + hex);\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>When I call this method it gives my this <code>NumberFormatException</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>java.lang.NumberFormatException: For input string: \"0xff0000\"\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>I can't understand what's going on. Can someone please explain?</p>\n"
}